From: synthmodem vendor
Subject: [PATCH] v22bis: increase rx power meter averaging shift from 5 to 9

The V.22bis RX carrier detector feeds the real part of the narrowband
RRC-filtered signal into a power meter that uses shift=5 -- i.e. a
~4ms (32-sample at 8kHz) exponentially-weighted average. With real
phone-line audio (particularly PCMU-decoded samples from a SIP call),
the filter envelope naturally dips near zero at QAM symbol
transitions, and 4ms of averaging is not enough to smooth those dips.

The observed rx_power.reading oscillates between ~900 and ~60000,
straddling the default carrier_off_power threshold of 955. Each dip
below that threshold calls v22bis_restart(), a full modem reset that
wipes tx.training back to INITIAL_TIMED_SILENCE.

On real modem connections this fires dozens of times per second and
causes V.22 training to fail permanently (TX goes silent within ~600ms
of first signaling, then the state machine never recovers).

Changing shift to 9 gives ~64ms averaging, which is:
  - slow enough to smooth the QAM envelope dips completely
  - fast enough to still detect a genuine carrier-loss within 100ms

Tested against a captured real-modem V.22 answer session: training
succeeds in ~1s, zero spurious restarts, 491 bytes decoded off the
line in an 8s window (vs zero before the patch).

--- a/src/v22bis_rx.c
+++ b/src/v22bis_rx.c
@@ -1020,7 +1020,16 @@ int v22bis_rx_restart(v22bis_state_t *s)

     s->rx.carrier_phase_rate = (s->calling_party)  ?  DDS_PHASE_RATE(HIGH_CARRIER_FREQUENCY)  :  DDS_PHASE_RATE(LOW_CARRIER_FREQUENCY);
     s->rx.carrier_phase = 0;
-    power_meter_init(&s->rx.rx_power, 5);
+    /* synthmodem patch: shift was 5 (~4ms averaging at 8kHz), which left
+       the power reading oscillating within the carrier hysteresis band for
+       the narrowband-filtered QAM envelope. Any dip below carrier_off_power
+       (~955 with default -45.5 dBm0 cutoff) triggers v22bis_restart() -- a
+       full modem reset that wipes tx.training back to INITIAL_TIMED_SILENCE.
+       On real modem audio fed through PCMU decode, this fires dozens of
+       times per second and causes training to fail permanently.
+       Shift=9 gives ~64ms averaging -- stable across symbol transitions,
+       fast enough to still detect real carrier-off in <100ms. */
+    power_meter_init(&s->rx.rx_power, 9);
     v22bis_rx_set_signal_cutoff(s, -45.5f);
 #if defined(SPANDSP_USE_FIXED_POINT)
     s->rx.agc_scaling = (float) (1024.0f*1024.0f)*0.0005f*0.025f;
